1. Vision

DAOSys aims to revolutionize how DAO based finances and governance is handled. By eschewing governance methods used by traditional DAOs, such as direct voting, in favor of self-sovereignty financial controls based on debt DAOSys solves many of the past problems of DAOs. This way, DAO members can be assured that their contributions are respected and used in furtherance of the DAO’s goal, whether financial or material.

2. Value Proposition

DAOSys uses proven applications of collateral and debt to secure user deposits, termed Treasurers. Combined with the DAOSys factory system, users of a DAOSys platform may deploy vaults to securely allocate their capital for several purposes. The financial security of debt collateralized with interest bearing assets provides the flexibility to define a variety of economic relationships. This is done under a financial system similar to bonds.

The basis of the DAOSys process is securing user deposits under a bond maturing based on the value of their interest bearing deposit and the debt load of the vault This protects against capital flight. The tokenized bond is credited at an exchange rate that represents the market driven maturation period for their deposit. As the bond matures through rebasing the bond token, a user may use their bond as collateral to borrow capital from the vault liquidity provided by all users. This is how DAOSys protects against capital flight. Because a user is receiving a bond on their deposit, they must wait for the bond to mature to realize a profit by extracting capital. The bond maturation rate is surfaced through the exchange rate for purchasing the bond. This ensures that the debt load of the vault does not reach unsustainable levels. The debt owed to fulfill the bond is satisfied by users borrowing from the vault. The interest bearing position used as collateral for this debt is further tokenized and partially sold through a debt market. The interest earned from that collateral, and the proceeds from selling bonds bonds backed by that collateral provides the interest needed to pay the interest due to other bond holders. In effect, a depositor may borrow from themselves, sharing the interest from their collateral to other users for providing the liquidity for lending. This means that purchasing bonds is similar to entering an investment tranche with assured interest secured from borrowers to fulfill the bond. By offering a debt market to incentivize repayment, the vault secures depositors from the actions of the others when they borrow capital for any reason.

This process of mediating the relationship of vault depositors through interest bearing collateralized debt allows the DAOSys platform to secure the finances and interest of involved parties. DAOSys offers configurable vaults that allows users to define the terms of the debt relationship and the administration of the finances. A DAOSys vault may be used for purely financial purposes, allowing Treasurers to manage their capital allocations to the vault. Alternatively, a DAOSys vault may be used to manage finances for a specific venture, termed Quest. By applying a variety of options to vest, escrow, sell debt, and distribute funds to execute a Quest, Treasurers, termed Councilors when governing a Quest, may govern the distribution of assets for a Quest.

A user may choose to take part in executing a Quest under the governance terms for that Quest vault. A user undertaking a quest is termed the Questor. DAOSys provides a means for Treasurers to mature their position from a Treasurer to a Chancellor. This process is how DAOSys provides means for dispute resolution between Councilors and Questors. A Chancellor may arbitrate a dispute by allocating assets owned by a vault to offer financial compensation to the claimant.

DAOSys secures the interests of Questors by allowing Treasurers to take the role of a Councilor through securing compensation for the Questor by using the capital allocation from the Treasurer as collateral to borrow assets and place them under an interest bearing escrow to vest during execution of the Quest. The exact terms for this vesting configured by the Treasurer deploying the vault and providing the initial funding.

3. Glossary

  • Vault - Vault Pool

A vault pool is the smart contracts that define a vault asset management pool. The configuration of a pool of what secondary markets it integrates with and how it produces and manages tokens defines the asset management strategy for a pool. A pool allows a user to deposit assets in the vault, and manage their allocation with the pool. The pool tokens produced by a pool allow a user to manage their allocation across pools, or trade their position in a pool.

  • $T - Token

Any token that does not come from the vault. This may be tokens accepted for deposit, or tokens the vault borrows and directly surfaces for use in the market.

  • Base Asset

Another name for an external token. But distinguished from a token by indicating that a base asset is not interest bearing directly due to it’s basic functionality. WBTC would be a base asset. DEX LP tokens would not count as a base asset due to their inherent complexity. A pool may have several base assets.

  • $IBT - Interest Bearing Token

Any token, or position the vault tokenizes internally for capital allocated to an interested bearing position. This may be liquidity pool tokens from DEXes or pools tokens from lending markets as an example. If a protocol, like Maker, does not produce a token to track interactions then the vault will represent the integration through rebasing tokenization.

The typical process is to accept a token for deposit into a vault pool that the pool can move into an interest bearing position integrated with the pool. A user’s deposited is credited based on the result of this deposit. Thus, if a user is depositing $T1 into a DEX liquidity pool of $T1/$T2, the $IBT would be the DEX liquidity pool token. The user’s deposit is credited in the resulting $IBT, or virtual $IBT implemented by the vault for integration. The vault holds the $IBT on behalf of the user, and provides them a derivative to track their deposit and the interest being earned.

  • $TT-IBT - Interest Bearing Pool Treasury Token

This is a token produced by the vault to track a user’s capital allocation into a pool. The $TT-IBT is implemented as a token similar to a Uniswap pair, an existing token standard extended to provide additional functionality as a pool. A $TT-IBT pool is implemented as a ERC-1155 with ERC-777 extensions with external ERC20 facades to provide integrations with legacy protocols. The token IDs are used to track a user’s total position in a pool. This is provided to the user as a NFT that provides the interface for that pool. This ensures access to a pool independent of SystemDAO, providing extra security to the users. A user interacts with the pool primarily through the ERC-1155 and ERC20 interfaces. The ERC-777 extension applied to ERC-1155 allows for the ERC20 facades to act as operators on the ERC-1155. By storing the token balances for a pool in the ERC-1155, and administering access through the ERC-20 facades the $SYS-IBT can be implement with additional internal behavior that facilitates managing pool assets.

The configurable functionality of a $SYS-IBT is provided by a on-chain factory to deploy proxies configured to use contract logic modules executed following an assembly line style workflow design pattern. The proxies deployed by a factory map a workflow to a token ID, the range of 10 - 100 is reserved for pool tokens. The remainder of the available token IDs available under ERC-1155 are used for a NFT provided to the user as vault. Interacting with the ERC-1155 and ERC-20 facades allows a user to manage their position in a vault. The range of token IDs 0 - 9 is reserved for platform administrative access.

  • $TT - Treasury token

$TT indicates the umbrella token that indexes the total value of the treasury. This is the DAO and treasury token referenced abstractly elsewhere in this document. There are several intermediary integrations used internally by the vault to aggregate the data from multiple sources to calculate the index. These integrations are tokenized as rebasing derivatives of $TT specific to the pool. The indexes are surfaced proportionally by rebasing $TT when those indexes are updated by a user interacting with a pool.

$TT is what users are earning through a process similar to a bond. By depositing into a pool with an accompanying strategy, the user will receive the rebasing pool token derivative representing their deposit. This token will be quantified in the chain’s native token, based on the closest available price source. By aggregating the supplies of the pool tokens, $TT is also quantified in the chain’s native token.

Tokens are distributed to depositors to represent the portion of the treasury of which they have self-ownership. This self-ownership provides the holder with control of their share of the treasury to be allocated through the staking pools available from the vault. The $TT held by the vault on behalf of the user acts as a type of collateral to ensure that capital is allocated in the manner the vault has deemed safe for other holders. Thus, depositors have full control of their deposit, but with restrictions similar to investment in a private venture in traditional finance.

A user matures their position in a pool by trading that for $TT. With $TT, a user may come to any pool that accepts $TT and use it as a claim on on unclaimed collateral in that pool. The ability to allocate $TT is limited by the available liquidity of unclaimed capital. And like a pool token, can only be used as collateral to extract capital. Thus, $TT serves as a kind of governance token by having the right to allocate unclaimed capital in a pool ll the way through the debt market if desired. A holder of $TT may leave unclaimed capital in a pool to allow the debt market resolve itself. Or, they may stake their $TT to claim a portion of the available liquidity, taking it off the market, but not introducing additional debt. Or, the may influence the debt market by borrowing against that unclaimed capital. The ability to influence the market for a pool is limited by the value the holder would had to have introduced elsewhere in the vault ecosystem. This provides the market the ability to rebalance any imbalance a holder of $TT may introduce by being able to buy portions of the interest bearing collateral.

  • $DT - Debt Token

Any token, or position the vault tokenizes internally that represents debt owed by the vault on behalf of a user. This may be the "S" or "VD" debt tokens produced by Aave, for example. In cases like Maker, where the debt is not tokenized, the vault will internally tokenize that debt with an adaptor to make it conform with the software architecture.

  • $TDT-DT - Debt Bearing Treasury Debt Token

This is the inverse of $TT-DT. It tokenizes the debt for a particular pool and aggregates that by pricing the debt in the chain’s native coin and pushing that index to $TDT as users interact with the pool.

  • $TDT - Treasury Debt Token

This indicates the umbrella token that indexes the total debt owed by the vault on behalf of the users. This continuously rebases to ensure accurate indexing of the debt so that is is surfaced in the market as a supply change as fast as possible. The intermediary TDT-DT tokens handle the aggregation of each source of debt. The operation of $TDT is very similar to $TT. Because $TDT uses the same mechanism to surface an inverse interpretation of the same behavior, the name is inverted. This is done partly to leverage the subtle marketability of a pair name resulting in a palindrome which indicates the relationship between $TT and $TDT.

While $TT allows a holder to allocate proportional amounts of available liquidity across pools, staking their $TT for the pool token to indicate the utilization. And farming more $TT through the maturation process. $TDT allows a holder to claim rights on capital allocated as collateral by disencumbering it of debt. The configuration of a pool determines exactly how this is done. The base process is for a pool to accept $TDT for deposit in exchange for the pool’s $TT-IDT disencumbered of debt. The pools will typically do this by selling the deposited $TDT into the debt market configured for that pool. The asset purchased is then used to repay the vault debt with whatever protocol the pool is integrated. The repayment of debt results in a contraction of supply of the pool’s $TDT-DT and $TDT overall. This effectively burns those tokens upon repayment. By contracting the supply of the debt tokens, the collateral the vault has deposited that is not encumbered by collateral based on the pool’s configured LTV thresholds can be priced using a constant product formula. The difference in supplies prior to the debt repayment and after debt repayment serves as the comparison that is done optimistically in the Uniswap implementation. Thus, the constant product formula will work by using the amount of capital obtained by selling the $TDT as the amount paid for the vault’s supply of the pool’s $TT-IBT be calculating the price using the supplies prior to repayment. The amount due from the calculated exchange rate will be what is safely available to release for reallocation after the debt repayment is processed. This way the implementation can be simplified by simply using the supply values at the start of the transaction, allowing the rebasing of those tokens to surface the relevant data needed to process the exchange once the start of a transaction has frozen the economy until completion.

  • ACL - Access Control List

Any configuration in a system that limits access to that system. This can be done either explicitly, such as defining a set of addresses that may interact with a contract. Or may be done implicitly by verifying the pedigree of an address by verifying the address against a calculation of that address based on immutable properties that can retroactively be trusted if the address calculation matches.

4. Pool Investment Strategy Structure

Strategies for investment pools consist of phases a user may choose to go through with their share of the treasury. The phases allow a user to determine how their share of the treasury is being managed within a pool.

4.1. Pool Phases

  • Entry Phase

  • Bonding Phase

  • Liquidation Phase

  • Maturation Phase

A pool must begin with a Entry Phase definition. If a pool has more then one phase it must end with a Maturation Phase. A Bonding Phase must come before a Liquidation Phase. There may be any number of Bonding and Liquidation Phases between the single Entry and Maturation Phases.

The phases may be defined with a combination of the following components.

  • Interest Bearing Position

  • Lending Market

  • Debt Market

A Entry Phase must begin with a Interest Bearing position. If the Interest Bearing position can be used as collateral on a secondary lending market then the Entry Phase may lead to a Bonding Phase. If the Interest Bearing Position cannot be used as collateral then it can not lead to a subsequent phase.

If a pool uses an external protocol that offers distinct vaults, the pool maintains a single vault for that pool.

5. Treasury Management Strategies

The following diagrams show the abstract process of pool operation. These diagrams only shows the pool functionality relevant ot that scenario.

5.1. Single Asset Lending and Debt

While the holder is staked, they are earning a claim on $TT. When a user deposits, and do not choose to continue to leveraging that deposit, they are credited the result of moving their deposit into the configured interest bearing position. Because the vault must hold some $TT and $SYS-IBT in order for the system to work the $SYS-IBT and the $TT from this deposit cannot be released to the user until maturation. The vault does this by tracking a user’s immature positions by crediting those positions to a NFT held by the user. With the NFT acting like a numbered account for the vault. A holder of the NFT has control of the positions credited to that NFT. While a user leaves their tokens staked in the NFT, they are providing liquidity for new entry.

Because the first deposit is the only factor contributing to the the $TT-IBT which is the only factor contributing to the supply of $TT at this point, the price of $TT-IBT to $TT is 1:1. The first depositor receives a NFT representing this stake.

The results of this initial, immature bond on $TT are covered in the later scenarios. These are presented as options on how to define the economic relationship between any parties initiating the vault with the first pool.

5.2. Second Deposit in Immature Pool.

Subsequent deposits are priced based on the staked supply of tokens. When a user deposits new capital, the vault forces a rebase of the $SYS-IBT is needed and captures the current balance held by the pool unencumbered with debt. The vault then moves the users deposit into the interest bearing position, and forces a rebase again if necessary. The vault then provides the user with the difference in the balance the vault sees in the supply it holds minus a configurable transaction fee if desired.

Because no deposit has been matured, or encumbered by debt, the total supply of the $TT-IBT for this pool is staked. This means the vault is fully exposed to the rebase. This is why the $TT-IBT for a pool can not be released to a user. A holder of bare $TT-IBT receives a disproportionate amount of interest from new deposits. To respect that encumbering a position with represents an assured claim on the interest bearing position and debt later during maturation, any encumbered supply is excluded from the vault holdings as they are in the NFT vault for users. This means that once any supply of a pool’s $TT-IBT is encumbered by debt, the percentage of unencumbered $SYS-IBT is the percentage of the deposit the user will see credited to them.

The result of depositing into a maturing pool is covered later in later scenarios to explain the impact of the debt market.

5.3. Second Pool Reinvestment

User are able to deposit into multiple pools at the same time. Even though a user is not given any $TT-IBT, through their NFT, they can have a pool borrow from another pool on their behalf. Because a pool can verify that another pool came from the same factory.. This allows users to leverage from one to another without having to mature to $TDT to do so.

When a user selects the $TT-IBT of pool for deposit into another pool from the same factory each pool verifies the pedigree of the other pool. After verification, a pool borrow on behalf of a user with the $SYS-IBT they choose to use as collateral. Because the loan is from pool to pool, the borrowed capital can be released to the other contract without having to taking advantage of it’s option to sell the debt. The $TT-IBT of the first pool is kept with the user’s NFT, with the accompanying $TDT-DT for that pool. The capital borrowed is released to the other pool. The other pool then processes the deposit and credits the user with the resulting $TT-IBT for that pool.

5.4. Recursive Capital Reinvestment

The process of leveraging from a pool to extend the user’s position in that same pool is in the diagram to the right. Because the user already hold pools tokens they be able use those to borrow from this pool for reinvestment in this pool. This process is almost identical to reinvestment in a second pool. In both of these scenarios show the result of if these deposits are done into mature pools.

5.5. Subsequent Deposit Into Maturing Pool

Once a user has encumbered part of their position with debt their only option is to leverage into a new pool, or to mature into $TT or $TDT. When a user matures to $TT or $TDT they trade the underlying position and any debt to the vault. Because of this, the $TT-IBT used as collateral will end up being owned by the vault. This provides a reliable return from that secured interest bearing asset used as collateral.

5.6. Capital Leverage To External Address

The process of leveraging a position to allocate capital to an external address involves selling shares of the collateral through a debt market. This is for any address that the pool can not verify the pedigree of. This means that the vault exercises it’s right of first refusal on buying the shares being allocated as collateral to take out capital. This is done by pairing the borrowed capital with the $TDT and starting a DEX pool. The vault keeps the DEX LP tokens.

5.7. Subsequent Capital leverage to External Address

The process of borrowing capital through an existing debt market is almost identical to the initial creation of the market. The only difference is that the capital borrowed is traded by the vault for $TDT to give to the borrower. This puts control on exactly when to close the position in the hands of the borrower. This way, a borrower may choose to hold their $TDT, and allow further debt accrual, and price action on the debt market to provide a different return. Should there be no action, the proportional allocation of debt from this pool, and other pools will create a slight differential on the correlation. This slight difference in correlation due to the aggregation of all debt into this market, surfaces the overall vault debt load and as compared the impact of the $T1 if reintroduced to the vault as debt repayment. If this does not provide a good exchange rate for entry through debt repayment due to low utilization, it is likely more advantageous to reintroduce this capital through a direct deposit into an interest bearing position as entry into a pool somewhere in the network. A high value future enhancement is the development of a router similar to Uniswap or Balancer that can find the best route at a given time. This can likely be delegated to 1Inch as either an obvious enhancement they will make, or through partnership as this introduces a completely novel from of trade routing.

6. Economic Theories

6.1. Risk Free Value (RFV)

Risk Free Value (RFV) is the process of ensuring the value of a pair of assets when the value of one of those assets is variable. This can be applied when the value of both assets is variable, this is Double Risk Value and explored later in this document. This can also be applied to actualize a Risk Free Value with a single asset, provided the circulation of that asset can be strictly controlled and indexed within an economy. When a strictly controlled asset actualizes a Risk Free Value for itself it is called a Recursive Risk Free Value.

The value of an asset in a market, its "price", can be pegged to a certain value if a reserve of the pricing asset is maintained in relation to the priced asset.

Provided a reserve of the pricing asset is held at the same ratio to the indexed market as the circulating supply of the priced asset a Risk Free Value is actualized.

This is the premise behind most pools in decentralized finance. The variation arises in how the priced and pricing assets as managed. A Constant Product decentralized exchange liquidity pool enforces a floating peg based on the reserve of each token. Effectively maintaining a reserve of each asset as backing for the other on a curve which defines the floating peg price. An important factor in the ability of a DEX to enforces this floating peg price is the impact of the circulating supply of the priced asset. Provided the entire circulating supply of the priced asset is distributed through that pool, then the DEX can enforce the floating peg. This appears in the rising price floor enforced by a DEX through the application of Constant Product pricing. If the entire circulating supply is distributed through the DEX pool, then this would be a hard price floor. This is because there is no way to add more to the DEX’s supply of the asset without introducing more of the other asset, maintaining the backing. If there is a supply in circulation that has not been distributed with the DEX pool, then it is possible to introduce more of the priced asset into the pool with an additional amount of the pricing asset. This means that the DEX can only enforce a soft price floor. This is essentially the same as the Fully Diluted Market Cap. But algorithmically enforced through the deterministic execution of the smart contract acting as the DEX pool.

A utilization based decentralized multi-collateral lending pool is managed much the same way. The collateral held is the priced asset. The borrowed asset is the pricing asset.

In a multi-collateral single asset lending pool the RFV for the pricing asset leaving the pool is maintained by holding the priced asset as collateral with the option to sell the collateral on a market used to calculate the value of each asset.

When the value of both assets is variable in comparison to the other based on the value of each in the underlying market a Double Risk Free Value can be achieved by actualizing the Risk Free Value of each asset. In this case each asset is pricing the other to define the floating peg price used to actualize the RFV. This allows for several combinations of assets as collateral and loan proceeds. The LTV between the collateral and the loan proceeds can be defined based on the loan structure.

A Basic Double Risk Free Value can be actualized from accepting a position in the underlying market as collateral. A self-funding loan can be established by compounding the loan proceeds into the market position. This way, interest can be automatically collected in distributed to lenders by securing the original collateral and the resulting compounded market position.

7. Investment Pool ABI Abstract

  • doesAcceptToken(address) returns (bool)

Allows for querying a pool to determine whether a pool will accept a token for deposit. This may be done by verifying the pedigree of the token contract, and/or based on the tokens the pool is configured to use.

  • doesProduceToken(address) returns (bool)

Allows for querying a pool on whether a pool can produce a token. This answered based on whether a pool can produce a token if interacted with properly. These would include the $TT, $TDT, $TT-IBT, and any base asset a pool may lend.
